sec.p:
For given exposed atoms of a protein X, we can calculate the k-th convex hull (CHk(X)) for each residue. The cumulate k-th convex hull of X (denoted as CHk(X)) is defined as the union of k convex hulls, i.e. CHk(X) = ∪i = 1..k{CHi(X)}. Obviously, CHm(X) is a strict subset of CHn(X), if m<n. If a residue is in CHi(X), then this residue is also in the cumulate i-th convex hull CHi(X). Clearly, we can choose a finite value K0 for which CHk(X) will cover (contain) all the exposed epitopes on the protein surface. K0 is defined as follows:




K0=min{k|all epitopes∈CHk}


